social_posts.post_text:
I had the best visit with my Mom over Thanksgiving!
We had a blast cooking for Thanksgiving and decorating for Christmas. I had some of my local girlfriends over, and we laughed and played games. Mom got to visit with some good friends who moved here from Jersey. I even got to take her to our new church!
We did SO MUCH!
She cooked for me and made my lunch.
My house is SPOTLESS!!

This has been a super hard year for me.
I am so thankful for my Mom and that I still have her and that she can come when I am overwhelmed and sad.
It's such a blessing that when I need her, she can still be a flight away.
Hug your people.
Tell them you love them.
Love you, Mommy! ❤️🥰

It's been a bit quiet around these parts, but trust me when I tell you that in my off line work? I am present and pushing hard.✊🏾❤️💪🏾

Lemme offer some free advice: 
There is far too much 'influencing' then quitting teaching going on this app. Prepping pics and posts is actual WORK. When your job is taking all you have? 
You will most assuredly burn out by trying to keep up on this app. If you want a 20 year career? Read books that improve your teaching. Spend real life time with other professionals that grow rather than drain you. Organize like minded folks in that work. Sit in all of your various off line identities and thrive.
Pursue balance.

Latergram it.

Your story is being written right now, and it's up to you to make the moves you need to in order to keep yourself going forward instead of back. 

This system thinks they are burying us....we are seeds though. ✊🏾

If you've followed me for some time, you may have heard me talk about 'teaching seasons'. When I look back at my career, I know with surety that I have navigated each season multiple times. I can look back at my social media and recall exactly what season it was by my posts, or lack of posts. Thinking of my years in the classroom in terms of seasons has helped me to navigate within them, but also gives me hope.
A brief word on winter:
It is stark, but also beautiful. 
It can feel isolating, but does not require loneliness. 
Where things may seem dead, there is life waiting to emerge under the right conditions.
One thing that I cling to on the rough years is my peers. Could be teammates, maybe not. Being with the right people recharges me. Inspires me. Encourages me.
Pouring into others gives me a great deal of joy, but winter requires me to conserve my energies.
I hold in tension my desire to do more, while recognizing that doing less is what needs to happen so that I begin to thrive, rather than just survive.
Time away from school has been so precious--not because I don't love my job, but because sometimes I love it too much and don't love myself enough. 
I share these reflections with you in the hope that you know you are not alone. That others with much more experience are also struggling, but pressing on. That we are always better in community.
I am thankful for the community that I have and that supports me in real time.
I pray your time away helps to remind you of the good in this calling too. ❤️

Y'all.
I have been working with a ton of rookie teachers over the last decade or so. I'm gonna tell ya.
They are on this app, and depending on so many of us to get them through.
The non-nuanced advice is killing them.

Lemme give a few examples:
Relationships over everything. 
What does that even mean? Should they let kids act a fool and make sure they are always the relatable teacher?

Here's another:
Stop taking work home.
So....um...who gon grade these papers and write these lesson plans and call these parents and understand this curriculum? Who?

A final one:
Close the door and teach...another variation? Do you, boo.

Here's what I am asking you to consider as you share this year. What practical steps could you offer that make your sound bite advice clear? Could a teacher with limited experience follow the breadcrumbs you are dropping....to new learning for THEMSELVES? Not a product. 

Look...I'm not on here to bash content creators. I sell on my blog and TPT. What I AM saying is...teach people to fish. Don't just give them one. I'm asking you to do honest mentoring here and not shortcut. 

Being engaged on this app as a content or curriculum leader means teaching. Please teach.
Thanks. ❤️

Y'all.
The real ones looked like this at some point during break.
Cause what is NOT getting ready to happen is me not knowing what I am doing or not feeling ready to jump in when I get back. 

It's NEVER perfect. 
You can't ever 'work until you are finished' in teaching, but you can work on what is most important and let small things slide to later on your calendar.

A few things that I try to get done first are:
Grades
Data analysis 
General lesson plans 
Gathering up necessary materials for lessons & thinking through procedures for use. 

For me....and this is just about preference, but aesthetics wait until the end. Anchor charts & bulletin boards are cute and fun, but I tend to be particular and they take me too long. 

I would much rather create my own materials based on standards than search TPT. I have a few sellers that I follow and have used their ideas, but most things I do myself because I want to really reflect my learners.

Last thing, basal curriculum is NOT the enemy. Just because it's dry or hard to get through doesn't mean you can't use it as a spring board and tweak it to fit your style. Full transparency, this is my first year in fourth. Fl has all new standards and our district adopted new reading curriculum last year and new math this year. Combine that with being new to the grade level? I feel a lot of pressure. I have been pretty focused on our literacy series and working on integration of social studies this year. The math series I have used with fidelity exactly as presented but am making notes on adjustments for NEXT year.  Rome wasn't built in a day. Creating for each subject area WELL takes time. 

I'm going to get back to work here.
Happy New Year to you and yours! ❤️
May 2023 be our best year yet!

Let me explain what that looks like for me and see if it resonates.
I feel like I am ready to go home on Friday, so I take a bag of school stuff home. I am busy living my life that weekend, so I feel guilty when I pass it and think of what needs to be done. Sunday night late,  go through it and get distracted again. Monday I am waking up early to try and get to some of it that has to be done before teaching and I am stressed because I am late and didn't get coffee, forgot to pack lunch, or both.
That's exhausting and demoralizing. 
Teacher guilt is real over so much.
I am pretty sure one of the reasons my workload is heavy is because this year, I am new to a lot. New grade level, new curriculum, new procedures at school, new administrators and coaches...etc. In order to really understand where my students are with new standards and curriculum,  I am grading a ton. I DO feel better about knowing how to help them, but initially, it took too much time away from me doing what fills me up.
An adjustment I have made is to stagger my work. There are weekends like this one, where I planned to do nothing because there was a lot going on for me personally. Last weekend. I worked ahead and I am all set except for two engineering projects I need to design for my STEAM Club members. That can wait, though, because it is Tuesday. 
Another thing that is helping is electronic grading where I can. This week, I will have several after school activities. I have planned to require less graded work this week...or make it electronic to ease my burden a bit. 
The reality is, teachers have always worked from home. It will continue. What's toxic is feeling bad for living your life because of your job. This post-Covid landscape has all of us taking on WAY TOO MUCH. Go easy on yourselves.❤️

TW: Loss

Today, I will say a final and forever goodbye to a student.
Y'all.
He was beautiful and bold. Spontaneous and soulful. Intuitive and sweet.
The year I taught him was one of deep retrospection and growth. 
It marked me in ways I am just now able to articulate fully. 
His loss is immeasurable for those who loved him. 
16 years wasn't enough, and yet, that's all we got.
If you are a person of prayer, please do.
His mother and siblings are such beautiful souls, and their heartbreak is real.
There aren't really words you say to a parent who lost a child. I am sorry feels like not enough. I pray my presence and that of others today will remind his Mom once again how deeply her son was loved when he crossed each of our paths.
Love you, TJay. ❤️

Imma beg y'all.
In 2022?
Leave the colorblind, lovey dovey sentiments about Dr. King off your timeline.
We need folks ready to put boots on the ground to get into good trouble.
We need action.
We need a revolution in this system we call public ed.
Remember the truth of who he was.
If you are not familiar with him as a revolutionary, you don't know Dr. King, period.
We need to be inspired to work collectively in whatever way we can to disrupt this system and move towards change.
THAT is his legacy.
We've got this, people. 
It truly is THE moment.
✊🏾💜

This school year, I am being held together by Jesus and the people who love me. ❤️
I think I can finally say that what I've been experiencing this season is an immense grief. As an Enneagram 4, I am a deeply feeling person. All the physical and intangible losses this season have had me reeling.
Yesterday, I had a night out with some of my dearest friends, and it was such a blessing. 
Joy is an important part of resistance and while in grief, it's hard to remind myself of that. 
I know that lots of us who are teachers are struggling for a mirad of reasons, but coupled with personal stuff outside of school it can seem so overwhelming. 
Make sure you take care of yourself through counseling and community.
We are NEVER alone, and our feelings are valid. 
If you are off today, make sure you do what fills you. 
Be blessed. ❤️

Teaching in this state right now is a lot.

Y'all send us positive vibes, prayers, thoughts, and coffee. ❤️☕️

What I pray is that we will find solidarity in organizing for the good of all teachers who are getting into good trouble and pushing back on racist narratives that preserve inaccurate versions of history over truth.

I am a Black educator. 
I can do no less than tell the truth about our collective stories. 
This Black history month will find me telling the same truths that I have my whole career.

May each of us go boldly into this season, rather than stay in silent appeasement. 

Onward, Florida educators! ❤️✊🏾
Courage! Even when your voice shakes!

God bless this unstaged mess!❤️🤣
Remember teachers, if you wait to post until it's perfect, you may find that you lose the joy of organically sharing what you loved in an experience with students. It doesn't have to be perfect to be relevant or effective. ❤️

As the coach of a competitive STEAM team, I get tons of opportunities to create engaging lessons. My closet is stocked with extra randomness. 🤣Every time I come up with some standards aligned hair brained scheme, my kids just come along for the adventure. I love them! ❤️

I started the lesson with a number puzzle. I just like to hear them reason things out. They are so fun to listen to! Then, we watched a short clip of someone riding a large coaster and discussed the experience. I had them  read about force and motion featuring roller coasters, next. Scholastic magazine has so many great articles! We discussed what we would need in order build a roller coaster using a ping pong ball to replicate the experience. I gave them the materials and about 5 minutes to discuss and brainstorm. They were given 2 sheets of construction paper, a Solo cup, tape, paper clips, scissors, toothpicks and 5 index cards. After 25 minutes, we had two teams with two coasters!! The discussions were so fun! They did so well!!

Being creative helps me in this season, so much! Watching students become creative with a lesson I made? Priceless! I hope this week you find joy in something too. ❤️

📣Calling all relational teachers!📣
We have reached the mid point of the year.
You have lead with relationships...so they KNOW you love them.
They. Will. Not. Break. If. You. Consistently. Discipline. 
But if your kids are starting to turn up?
You need these tips.
1. Don't beg.
Weakness in a classroom screams you don't know what to do. Most kids today are being raised to be a bit more independent. If you look like you don't know what to do? Bet....they will take over, because SOMEBODY has got to be in charge.
2. Pick up your cadence. 
Some of y'all may not realize that you are talking too slowly and instead of it helping understanding its making the lesson run too long and you're losing them...which animates off task behavior. Talk faster. Use gestures. Tell them to buckle up. They got this!
3. Tighten up transitions.
Reward those who are doing things efficiently and not wasting your time. Table points work great in my room. Thank them for valuing your time and everyone else's!
4. Put some base in your voice.
Now. I didn't say yell. I mean speak with authority. Don't do it every time you need something. Do it sparingly, but when it's reeeeally important.  Stop whining at these kids, y'all. They are not babies, and they will tune you out. If you are already yelling? You better switch up to whispering when you really want something done, because by end of February? Your kids will be in open rebellion. 
Said in love. ❤️
We really do got this.
Carry on, teacher! ✊🏾

What. A. Day.
I just got home a few minutes ago.
Awards were today! My kids did so well in the 2nd quarter.❤️
We had a science test right after though! 🤣 So no one got to go home! 🤷🏿‍♀️
#IAmThatTeacher
After school did union-y things and ended up getting interviewed by local news.
On my way home, I listened to @annaforflorida lead a conversation about HB 1 an awful piece of legislation meant to siphon more money away from public schools and give it to charters.
Y'all....how can money follow kids that aren't even transferring FROM public schools?
Just another day, another opportunity for our statehouse to attempt to privatize public ed.
Never a dull moment.
I am home now though!
Smells from my crock pot are amazing!
Shout out to hubby for finishing up with our roast so all I gotta do is get pj'd and grade these papers that won't go away.
Happy to be home!❤️

I am gutted by what I know about Tyre Nichols passing. I have been heartened by the video shared of him riding his skateboard and enjoying sunsets. This weekend, for my own mental health, I will find ways to make myself smile and laugh. Not because I want to ignore my feelings, but so that I remind myself that I can.
Be easy with yourselves. 
💜

Y'all.
Whew.
I'm tired of this.
Like....why?
(This is a rhetorical question.)
Sigh.
So, let me process out loud a bit.
Typically, after I am done being pissed about the waste of resources....

Oh....and also...I try to NEVER discipline when I am in that head space because I would be overly punitive. 

I start to think about all the patterns of behavior of both myself and the child.

All behavior is communication. 
So, what triggered this?
What were we doing right before this moment?
What is the child trying to communicate with destruction of property?
Is it my property? Theirs? Shared?
Were there signals the child was giving that I could have missed?
Was I in a space to be able to hear/see them at that time?

So much of these interactions can be deescallated if at least one party is cognizant that things are going in the wrong direction. 

I don't say this because as the teacher, I am *most* responsible, I say this because relationships require commitment and communication from BOTH parties and depending on the child, it is entirely possible that they are intuitive enough when they are in the right head space to notice and name when the teacher is feeling a "certain type of way".

The problem often comes in when we are both disregulated at the same time.
My working conditions are my students learning conditions, and I have to consistently work on not letting the stress of this season influence my teaching. I am holding in tension my desire to teach authentically and the pressure to push students because *I* feel pressure.

There's a tendency too to be less consistent when ruminating on your own complicity in behavioral escalations. We are human and can model apologizing when we make a mistake. 

So much learning from broken pencils. ❤️
Learning is HARD.
Give yourself grace as you reflect.

This year, I was part of a group of teachers that helped to coordinate Black History Month Activities for learners at my public school.
There is something so special about being with like-minded people. 🖤
This year didn't feel much different from others in terms of what I wanted to share. Each year, I strive to elevate the beauty and resilience of Black people particularly in February. I have done units on the Harlem Renaissance, the Underground Railroad, Scientists & Mathematicians, The Montgomery Bus Boycott too.
In January, I was asked to departmentalize, so I only teach math and science. That's not stopping me from taking 10 minutes out of the top of my lessons to introduce my kids to an influential Black American. 
Each day, I talk about a different Black American and on Fridays, we do a joy & culture lesson. 
Our reading classes are working on an American Revolution unit, so many of my famous African Americans are related to men and women connected to the time period or the military this year!
So many interesting stories to tell! 🖤
Let me remind you, there are so many rich lessons you can teach through the Florida Social Studies standards. One of the first things I do before planning a unit is looking there for alignment. 
You don't need to be afraid to teach history. You need to be more worried about what happens when you don't. 
Take heart, Florida teachers.🖤
Go forth in collective community and teach truth.
What are you focused on teaching for Black History Month, Florida teachers?

One thing I know for sure is that organizing with others who are like minded and purposed to create an environment in schools that is rich, equitable and warm will bear fruit. 

This weekend,  I am spending time doing just that.

I am a teacher in Florida public schools.
I am a proud unionist.
I believe Black History is American history.
I believe kids should read books that affirm them.
Staying quiet on the war against African American studies and LGBTQ+ folks doesn't make us safer, it makes us complicit. Stand UP, Florida teacher. STAND UP!

I believe that what the nation may pity and see as a lost cause is going to birth a resurgence of activism and energy. It's already starting. Watch our young people,  y'all.

Talk to your neighbors. 
Talk to your friends.
Put a face on 'public school teacher and unionist' for people.
We are NOT the problem.

Kids and teachers deserve better than this rampant anti-teacher foolishness and dismissal of basic autonomy and ability to teach truth!

Teachers are NOT superheroes. 
We are lifelong learners.
Learning is messy and full of a myriad of happy accidents and messy mistakes.
Allow teachers to learn.
Allow teachers to stumble in order to run.
Praise us for problem solving.
Listen when we call.
Offer support and then KEEP giving it.
Teachers and kids deserve better than this season we've arrived in.
So. Much. Better.

We made it!❤️
This week felt like so much.
There was a LOT of overwhelm.
The pace in fourth grade is bruising and I STAY worried that I am not getting to every kid in all the ways that I can. 
The work is never all the way done.
I am so thankful for my teammates that love and support me through it all.
There is nothing like community, folks. ❤️
I pray your community in or even out of school is loving and supporting you too. 
Good friends are such a blessing and encouragement!

Didn't I tell y'all about trash click bait takes out here? SMH.
Well....Twitter was hopping with them yesterday.
Note to leaders, consultants and edu-tainment influencers.....
At this point, edu-professionals are on to y'all.
We know you are tasked with keeping us 'motivated' this season. We know that your jobs depend on us making a miracle out of the systemic mess we are in.
Educators have been telling you for years we were in free fall and y'all didn't listen.
The solutions that I am seeing out here all look like..."Teachers do more for us and sacrifice yourself for the children and it will all be fine."
I mean...pick an issue...this is always the answer in some form.
Instead of actually pushing substantive change, leaders and edu-influencers have turned gaslighting campaigns into an art form. Chatting us up about self care, and rest, while expecting work outside contract hours and not taking sick days...because of 'the children' and now...colleagues.
This productivity over everything push is killing education spaces. There is too much pressure to perform everywhere.
Y'all stay not speaking to why teachers are STILL leaving this profession as if those of us in the trenches don't already know.
Stop making it harder on the rest of us by adding unrealistic expectations to how we use our time.
Mind your business!
Fix the sub shortage!
#endrant

It is time for my annual President's Day post. It brings me joy!
Y'all already know who my #foreverpotus is! 
Thankful too for the current president and VP. 💜 I am always more grateful now for this day, but I am even more deeply grateful for the time away from school to recalibrate. These moments are so important y'all. Hope you're well today!
Shout out to President Carter!
Panamanians will always thank you for giving back our canal.💜
A man of such purpose and deep compassion. 
Happy President's Day, America!
#39 #44 #46

Remember, that's the whole point.
I have been looking at how to better streamline my work load and cut things out to create more time for activism. 
I have been resting more at home instead of dreaming up new ways to do things at school.
There are times it makes me sad to not have the energy to do some of what I once did, but burning out won't serve me or this work. 
Remember that the goal of oppression is consolidation of power and resources. To make sure we are so busy fighting for our next breath, we don't have the energy to continue educating and mobilizing others to take a stand.
Take care of yourselves. 
This season will require us to stand in times where it would be easier or more convenient to hide or be silent.
Gather your strength. 
Fight for yourself and your colleagues. 
Stand up and with your students.
We are the ones we have been waiting for.
And trust me....they WANT you to burn out or quit so they can say that public schools are bad. If they are bad, federal, state and local policy have made them so. Teachers are just trying to do right by ourselves and these kids.
They know that TOGETHER, we can educate community members and other stakeholders about what is really going on. They want us demoralized so we won't. 
Chin up!
Shoulders back.
Stand strong, educator. ✊🏾💪🏾❤️

Friday was my birthday!
It was amazing!
I spent it with my union bae's over at FEA Winter Leadership!
Practicing one on one's in front of a roomful of people is a bit intimidating, but good for me too!
The trainings were incredible! 
Please keep your eyes and ears open for us here!
We are mobilizing and hopeful!❤️✊🏾

Because sleeping during this third Civil Rights Movement isn't an option.

@jemartisby wrote that 'Racism doesn't go away, it just adapts.' 

Living through this season as an educated AWAKE person both inspires and frightens me. If I ever wondered who I would be during King's time...who I am now, is who I would have been then. 

Who you are now, is who you would have been then too.

Pick an issue...there are so many to fight back on. Just fight.

Stand.

Speak.

Shout.

Disrupt.

Dismantle. 

Hold the line.

To be woke means to be aware of injustice and to mobilize against it.  It means to stand in solidarity with like minded folks. It means to organize for the collective good. It means to be unapologetically committed to collective liberation.

May we hold tightly to each other during this season and beyond, Florida teacher.

Glad I'm not in this alone.

#Onward

And just like that?
Spring break has sprung! ❤️
I am going to enjoy this few days of rest because if you heard, session in Tally is a LOT. I am going up at the end of the month, but this week they are fast tracking the anti-teacher's union bill among several others. 
Time to call your local reps and sentors, folks.
So much will be lost for us all if we lose our union.
#FlTeacher
#StayWoke
#Activism

I can't take credit for this.
It's inspired by a line from the movie The American President. 
I will tell you though, it still rings true.
We can't be willing to put up with foolishness just to 'not be a problem'. We need to move in solidarity instead of in isolation. We need to learn no is a full sentence.
I want teaching in our schools to be better for the teachers coming behind me. What's going on in Florida just ain't it. 
Headed up to Tally with members from my union to see if we can help lend our voices to the cause.
I will miss my students, but this is too important to not speak up. Kids need to know we are willing to fight for us, and them. 
✊🏾❤️

I'm sitting in the house gallery waiting for a few more education bills to get heard today. What a week.
So thankful to get a squeeze of encouragement from one of my favorites @annaforflorida.
We saw some other reps too! Representatives Campbell and Williams were in the elevator and helped us get back to the house chamber. Our personal reps Trunow and Yarkofsky met with us. 
So appreciative of the lawmakers who are fighting so hard for us.

This legislative cycle has been brutal.😔
I was heartened to go to Tally a few weeks back and speak with Democratic lawmakers who are pushing back and standing in solidarity with Floridians who are coming up weekly to speak with legislators, peacefully protest and organize. ❤️✊🏾
With the passage of the union busting bill this week, we have until October to reach 60% density in our local teacher's union or we will lose it and all of the collective bargaining rights our contracts afford us. 
At the same time, I am wrapping up year 2 with the most amazing group of fourth graders. We have seen each other through so much. It's been a year of transition and growth. As I move towards my last days with them before they move on to fifth grade, I have a new energy to make our days memorable and this part of the journey the best yet.
They give me hope for what is to come. Several have mentioned wanting to teach. I pray I always inspire little ones to do this career I love so much.
We continue to stay rebellious here.
We are not without hope.
We will fight every fight whether or not we win because sometimes it's not about winning.
It's about the joy in resistance. 
It's about a refusal to be silent about collective oppression.
It's about gathering strength in numbers.
We are still here....❤️✊🏾

You ever been in a professional funk?
Like...a moment where although you know you are purposed for something, but lately it's just not doing it for you?
I love classroom teaching...like REALLY love it. ❤️
I am coming off year two with a great bunch I looped with. 
Mid year, I was asked to departmentalize. Since Christmas, I have been teaching just math & science to mine and a partner teachers kids.
My other class is sweet too. I enjoy them, but it's so different when you long for the comfort of familiarity. Starting something mid year was tough. 
A broader narrative that I have been thinking about too--particularly as someone truly purposed for elementary school--is that the oppressive policies and expectations of both the state and federal level have put so many of us in a position that in order to increase learning gains, we end up breaking up elementary classes by subject areas like middle school. We spend more time thinking about the parts rather than the whole. 
I know it is easier.
As a lifetime elementary practitioner? 
I wonder what 'the best' looks like in this landscape. 
Can an old school teacher shift to this new trajectory permanently?
I don't know.
Maybe it's a season for change.
I know imma be in education.
I'm gonna be in a brick and mortar school. I'm not ready to let that go, yet.
But...maybe...what if it's time to start thinking about a new path.
❤️

People love to say "Build Relationships". The follow up question is always what does that look like?
For me, it's always been...
Be the teacher YOU needed.
I take time to listen to my kids.
I teach them how to advocate for themselves.
I honor their boundaries and expect them to honor mine.
I tell them I love them...especially when they have messed up or disappointed me. 
When I ask them about what they think I do when I am off from school...they say things like...sleep, read, make fun lessons for us. They also say things like come to my games! ❤️ 
They know I love teaching a lot and that I especially love teaching THEM. 
When I don't feel well, they make me hydrate and tell me to sit. They shush everyone.
It's sweet.
There is a LOT about teaching that is hard, especially now. As we come to the end of the year, give yourself grace and the kids. Listen more than you speak. Release them to do things and praise them for their effort.
Kids will be who you tell them they are.
Make sure you are speaking life.❤️

In seasons that are trying, you need to surround yourself with like-minded folks. I can't emphasize enough how important community is. 
It is essential! ❤️
This weekend, I was able to spend time with co-conspirators on PD for FEA. It is amazing to be with others who understand who you are and how you're feeling without having to explain yourself or pour from an empty cup into them. 
I feel full, y'all.
Something that came up in discussion  was 'Who are you reading?'
Might I exhort you to look at your most recent professional reads? How often are you reading from folks of the Global Majority to grow professionally? How often do you hold space for them and cite them?
Our professional reading is a reflection of our values. As you seek to be a better educator for all students, make sure your professional reading is a reflection of voices that are different than your own.
Thank you, Michael & Kimberly.
I am blessed to know you both!
Thank you for your friendship and solidarity!

Whew.

Some folks need to stay in their lane and just....you know....celebritate or whatever.

Don't mind me though....
Imma stay right here in my public school....loving and leading these kids...getting loved in return. ❤️🍎✊🏾👏🏾

Y'all...brush the dirt off your shoulder.
We know who we are and what we do. 

Be the teacher you needed always.

Remember who you are.

Go out and slay Monday, y'all.

Fourth quarter, baby!!

Let's get these kids across the finish line and off to a well deserved break.

We got this!

Scores aren't everything. 
They are something...but they don't encapsulate all of the experiences that students have in a year or show all of the circumstances that they weathered. 
I've seen 'high achieving teachers' who treat kids like crap are over punitive and awful teammates. I've seen incredibly humble, collaborative and deeply loved high achieving teachers too. I have worked with teachers who have hit their highest highs professionally on years they had the lowest scoring data on their team. I have worked with teachers who have average data that would probably be considered 'high achieving' if they chose a different school in which to serve.
If this country were half as obsessed with authentic learning for teachers and students instead of using standardized testing to demonize students and teachers, we would get somewhere.
There are many, MANY reasons that students perform the way they do on standardized tests. Chief among them is that learning is differentiated, yet assessment is standardized to those who create them. There's so much money invested in the same groups over performing the same groups. 
We all need to keep learning and crafting experiences for ourselves and students that help them become the young men and women they must be to lead this society. We must resist the urge to label ourselves or our students...particularly if we know the racialized history behind so much of what passes for assessment and the why behind it.

We hold in tension what we *thought* a profession in education would be and what it *is*. 
As we move steadily towards the end of another school year, I wanted to ruminate on a few things.
We all see that in many education spaces, the 'for the kids' set up typically means adding things beyond the scope of teaching to teachers' plates and blaming them when they can't keep all the plates spinning at once. We are given curriculum that doesn't work for kids, metrics that are unmanageable, timelines that are nonsensical, all while not being trusted to even pick books out for kids. We fund our classrooms to make them feel like home and yet....many of us are frought with anxiety and disappointment that leads so many into making the difficult choice to leave.
Support to help teachers manage all the spinning plates while at work is often not available until someone is not issued a contract to return. 
Might I suggest that YOU are always in the driver's seat of your career, whether you are in your first year or you 20th. You choose where you want to be and what you have capacity to deal with. This teacher's shortage means you interview *them* while they interview you. 
Go where you feel like you will GROW.
Stay where you feel whole and well.
Don't give up on this career if you felt it was for you in August, but now you just want to run.
Give yourself the chance yo try a new grade level, a new school, a new District, something outside of the classroom but still within education, go get a Master's.
Fight for this if it is what you want.
After 26 years?
It is still worth it.
I am glad I stayed even though there were times I felt just about pushed out.
After all, had I left...would you be able to learn from me in the ways in which you have?
I am glad I stayed.
Even if it was just for you that read this far and were encouraged to press on.

As a union leader in my district, there are a lot of things going on in Florida that just gut me right now. I won't pretend that the last several weeks have not been gut-wrenching for me to see on television and then go up to Tally myself and see with my own eyes. 
But joy is also resistance. 
Laughter is good for my soul. 
Dancing bring me joy.
House Democrats show up everyday to fight, KNOWING many of those fights they will lose because of the super majority. They still show up. They still smile. They still dance. They still fight. They still work. They still organize!
Recently a bill was passed that requires my local teacher's union to be at 60% density. We are also converting to EDues because the legislature passed a bill to prohibit us from doing payroll deduction. 
Tonight, I sat with fellow board members and we organized. We laughed, we vented, we strategized. 
I am endlessly thankful for these ladies and the others who make up our union board. The union is not just one person. It's all of us. Florida teachers, we need you to spread the word on Edues. We need you to ask colleagues to join our collective. We need you to commit to this union like it continues to commit to all of us. 
There is joy in collective action...not just because of the outcome....but because of the journey. Never forget that.

This is such a tough season.
As I continue to grow an anti-racist pedagogical lens and understand more intimately the varied ways in which testing harms students, teachers, schools and communities, I struggle with how much energy I put into seeing students perform on these tests.

As educators, so much is put on all of us when it comes to scoring data. As if our sole value to a space is contained in how well we move students. Moving students who have always been effective at testing feels different than what is done to help students who have been demoralized by those same tests. Moving students who are two to three years behind in one year is a skill, and those who do it consistently deserve respect. Period.

So much of testing in elementary school has to do with how a teacher can inspire kids to trust the strategies they've been taught and to use them. Yet, every year we see kids bested by anxiety and self doubt who fail at things that were routine just days before.

My learners are testing this upcoming week. I am sure there is some level of expectation on outcomes since I have had them for two years, but this year was so hard for us on so many levels. I am reminding myself that worrying now is just going to make me seem nervous to them, and they need my unwavering confidence and unconditional love more than ever.

I wish we could all say we didn't care...this doesn't matter...it's just 'one test'. While we wait for this season to eventually end, we continue to fight and push back in other ways. We speak up even when our voices shake.

Sending love to every teacher who like me has sympathy testing anxiety for kids whose brilliance is more readily seen through hands on tasks and interaction with peers.  Our kids are precious and amazing no matter what.

As we steadily move towards the end of the year, let me remind you that you are deserving of joy.

You are deserving of appreciation now more than ever.

I am so proud of us!

We continue to find ways to persist, resist and insist on learning for all.

Sending you all love and light!
Happy Teacher Appreciation Week to me....and you, and You and YOU!!! ❤️

Last week was our final union meeting for this school year. We had a small gathering at a local restaurant. The apps were great, and the connections were even better.

If we don't convert to Edues and have 60% density, essentially what we know as our union is over. In the most trying time of the year, we redouble our efforts to find ways to connect with teachers to save our professional organization. 
Y'all, what is happening to teachers across this state is not right. Check in on your Florida teacher friends. We are not okay. This...what is happening here is not okay. The only real way to protect ourselves is with a teacher's union.

Mentoring is one of the most fun parts of being a veteran teacher. I always try to be the mentor I wanted for myself. 
When you are the kind of person who builds capacity and relationship well? People will feel comfortable enough to learn from you and share with you.
When you realize that years in the classroom is not the only way to encapsulate knowledge? You come to see the energy and ideas of teachers with less years of experience as energizing rather than exhausting. 
It takes nothing to just listen and encourage. It's not my job as a veteran to tell people what to do. It is simply to walk alongside and encourage the type of reflection in daily practice that creates a lifelong professional learner.
I know we are tired and running low on energy, but I urge you, veteran teacher... Don't discourage younger teachers more than they are. Find a way to connect and support. Relationships and authenticity are never going out of style. You never know....you may make a lifelong friend! ❤️

I have made no secret of the fact that this year has been one of my hardest ever.
The professional expectations were extraordinary, and then I lost three kids to heaven. Two of which had been my students and one who was like family. This yellow bracelet is what I wear to remind me of the one who was family. It reminds me that no matter what, I should 'Spread Kindness' and 'Radiate Joy'. It's what our sweet Owen did with his life and what I will continue to carry until I see him again. 💛
Healing takes so many different paths. Sometimes, it takes us away from what we thought we wanted and on to new places and people. 
Next year, I am leaving my current school and moving to a different one. I'll be back in third grade teaching just math and science. This new place knows nothing about what has been a challenge for me. I can reshape my next steps by spreading kindness. 💛 I will connect with other teachers and help. I will love my new students with tenacity. I will hold the students I lost and sweet Owen in my heart. I will start over.
I already miss my kids at my old school and their families and Im not gone yet. They carried me more times than they know. 💛 
Change is hard y'all, but necessary. 
The end of the year brings a lot of mixed emotions for folks.
We can be both excited for summer and hold close to our hearts kids, teachers and families who have anxiety about their next season.
Be gentle with each other as you bring this year to a close. 💛

Some kids will want to count down, some will not.
Some will miss everyone and everything about their experiences, some will not.
Some will hold their emotions until they get home, some will not.

Know that some of their behavior could be their own stress about summer or moving to a new teacher.
Some behavior could just be excitement to be done....or lack of structure. 
Be kind to yourself and them.

This week, I am reading The Art of Teaching Teams by Elena Aguilar. I am so looking forward to utilizing some of her practical tips in the mentoring group I am developing with some other teacher-leaders in the union. 
This quote resonated with me greatly. 
Y'all already know standardized testing is killing the creativity of teachers and students. When, as a team, the main reason folks come together collaboratively is to 'raise achievement levels'? What happens when you aren't the number one on your grade level? Were you...unsuccessful? Were you a...failure?
How DO you measure a successful teaching year?
'Seasons of Love' a song from Rent gives us a glimpse.

🎼🎵How do you measure, measure a year?

In daylights, in sunsets
In midnights, in cups of coffee
In inches, in miles
In laughter, in strife
In five hundred twenty-five thousand, six hundred minutes
How do you measure a year in the life?

How about love?
How about love?
How about love?
Measure in love
Seasons of love
Seasons of love🎵

As you wrap up your year, lean in to all the different ways you grew. Resist the ways in which this system may reduce you to a singular data point. Remember that your school year had so many moments of love given and received. Then, with those realizations, begin to think about the goals that you have for yourself and your students that value your humanity and celebrate your growth.
Enjoy your summer! 🍎❤️👍🏾

Teachers are so determined to teach even in the most inhospitable conditions that we find grants and additional revenue sources--outside of contract time, yearly or at worst go out of pocket ourselves. 
I am in equal parts astonished and discouraged by how seamlessly we've moved into this transition over collective pushback.
It grieves me most because I am cognizant of how unsustainable this is for a 30 year career in teaching.
We deserve so much better, y'all.
As you look for the best ways to serve students remember that you don't need to go into debt to fund a classroom. If you love your students well, that makes up for a lot those first years especially. There's nothing wrong with sharing products, but sometimes you need to know that you, too, can make it.
That the tension you hold between loving this calling and loving yourself is real.
You can be incredibly dedicated to this profession and have a life outside of it.
Sometimes, you just need to be inspired. ❤️
I hope my account reminds you that a 30-year career isn't so far away. That it can be a joy rather than just a job.
You can meet people, have experiences, grow personally and professionally in ways that fill you up, and fight for what you believe in. 
I hope that is what you feel when you hold space in my little corner of the internet. ❤️

I am doing something new this year that I am excited about!
Here in FL, we have annual professional development goals we set for ourselves and work through with our administrator. We align those goals to our evaluation tool and monitor progress on them with data. We call ours a DPP.  Got something like this where you are too? What's yours called?
We have had this tool for a while, and a lot of things on it I have used... some multiple times just because I liked working on that. Interestingly enough, one I haven't done on our tool is support for multilingual learners. I have done lots of different things, but it was never my professional focus for a year.
Sometimes, it's easy to get bogged down in all the things that are tough about being a classroom teacher in Florida. It's hard to wrestle with all the things that feel as if they have been stripped away. 
In this professional goal, I am continuing to commit not only to elements of my personal culture being centered in my reading, thinking and doing, but I can be a stronger advocate for the students I serve in a challenging and complex time. This year, one improvement I am working on is turning my vocabulary wall into one that has both a visual and Spanish translation. Shout out to my mom, who helps me a ton with this! I am going over the words before putting them up and looking for cognates as much as possible. My multilingual learners have really enjoyed this immensely and practice often. I also speak to them in both English and Spanish whenever I can. It's been great for me to gain more confidence in my ability to communicate. 
Don't let this ol' foolish way that this government wants to talk about race and culture prohibit you from learning, y'all. It's always worth it. Nothing lasts forever, and this too will pass if we continue to grow and organize.
Sending y'all love!❤️

Some times in education?
We do things, just to do them.
Not because teachers asked for them.
Not because teachers have said it helps them.
We are driven by upper ups, who are driven by their upper ups, who are driven by the state upper ups, etc. 
When you can?
Just send an email.
Teachers need time to call parents, go to the bathroom, decompress with peers, make copies, reply to emails, complete paper work....all kinds of things.
Honoring their time as much as possible will help retention.
It's tough out here, but getting creative with how to give educators some autinomy and time back  will definitely help! ❤️
